  <section>
    <h2>Basic Data Types</h2>
    <p>
      Java has two categories of data types: primitive types (built-in) and reference types (objects). 
      Primitive types include integers, floating-point numbers, characters, and booleans.
    </p>
    
    <pre><code>public class DataTypes {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Integer types
        byte smallNum = 127;           // 8-bit
        short shortNum = 32000;        // 16-bit
        int num = 100000;              // 32-bit (most common)
        long bigNum = 9000000000L;     // 64-bit (note the L)
        
        // Floating-point types
        float decimal = 3.14f;         // 32-bit (note the f)
        double largeDecimal = 3.14159; // 64-bit (default)
        
        // Character and boolean
        char letter = 'A';
        boolean isTrue = true;
        
        // String (reference type)
        String text = "Hello, Java!";
        
        // Output
        System.out.println("Integer: " + num);
        System.out.println("Double: " + largeDecimal);
        System.out.println("Char: " + letter);
        System.out.println("String: " + text);
    }
}</code></pre>
  </section>

